{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Christ most directly states the journey's purpose when commanding Andreas (Andrew) from the seashore: to travel to Mermedonia and rescue his brother Matthew from captivity before he is killed and eaten by the cannibalistic inhabitants.[^1] This divine imperative is reinforced later upon arrival, when Christ appears and reiterates the tasks of liberation and conversion.[^2]\n\nIn Allama Iqbal's \"Ek haji Madinay ke raastay mein\" (*Bang-E-Dara Part 3*), the pilgrim most directly states his journey's purpose amid internal debate after his caravan is raided: to reach Madina (Yathrib) despite mortal peril, rather than turning back to Mecca, lest he face shame on the Day of Judgment.[^3] The Hijra's \"secret\"—fearless persistence toward the Prophet's tomb—embodies this resolve.[^4]\n\nIqbal's pilgrim has more freedom to turn back: his quest is self-driven by passion overriding fear and reason, with no supernatural compulsion or penalty for refusal (save personal/spiritual regret). Andreas, by contrast, voyages under explicit divine orders, having already sinned by initial hesitation; refusal would compound disobedience to God.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-4d1e78).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-655ebf).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/06-ek-haji-madinay-ke-raastay-mein/translation/#p-70cdb7).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/06-ek-haji-madinay-ke-raastay-mein/translation/#p-ebe69b).\n\n[^5]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-655ebf).",
